I'd for Sell in 15k non negotiableğŸš€ There are a few reasons why your husband might apologize even when he hasn't made a mistake. Here are some possibilities: Taking Responsibility for the Mood: Maybe there's a tense atmosphere and he wants to diffuse it. He might say sorry to acknowledge your feelings and show he wants things to be better, even if he doesn't believe he caused the tension. Avoiding Conflict: Some people dislike conflict and might apologize to end a discussion before it escalates. This doesn't necessarily mean he agrees with you, but he prioritizes keeping the peace. His Upbringing: His family background might influence how he apologizes. In some cultures, apologies are used more broadly to express empathy or smooth things over. Unconscious Habit: It's possible "sorry" is a verbal tic he uses without thinking. Here's how you can approach the situation: Open Communication: Talk to him directly and ask him why he apologizes in situations where you don't see his fault. Focus on Feelings: Instead of dwelling on who's right or wrong, express how his apologies make you feel. Alternative Approaches: If his apologies feel insincere, suggest alternative ways he can show he cares about your feelings during disagreements.

The bonds that once felt unbreakable may slowly erode, leaving behind echoes of shared memories overshadowed by the stark reality of unfamiliarity. Sudha Murty, an educator, author, philanthropist, and former chairperson of the Infosys Foundation, serves as an influential figure for many people. As the first female engineer at TELCO, now Tata Motors, she successfully completed her engineering studies during a time when it proved exceptionally challenging for women to pursue careers in this field. Sudha Murty is married to N R Narayana Murthy, who co-founded Infosys. In a revealing interview on The Kapil Sharma Show, Sudha Murty disclosed that she provided her husband with a financial boost of Rs 10,000 to initiate his own company. The story unfolds when Sudha Murty, introduced to Narayana Murthy through her college friend Prasanna, made the decision to invest in her husband's business idea. In 1981, Narayana Murthy conceived the concept of Infosys, and Sudha Murty contributed Rs 10,000 from her personal funds. The Rs 10,000 loan extended by Sudha Murty played a pivotal role in the launch of Infosys in 1981, beginning from a modest one-bedroom apartment. Today, Infosys stands as one of the world's largest IT companies, with a market capitalization of Rs 6,10,000 crore. To this day, Sudha Murty regards her decision to support Narayana Murthy with Rs 10,000 as her "best investment." During an interview with NDTV, she humorously expressed that she may be "the best investor in India, at least, or perhaps in the world... I don't know."
